d.\n| 8000 - 15000 students\n| <ref>https://www.ayudamineduc.cl/ficha/examenes-libres-menores-de-18-anos-11</ref>\n|-\n| Colombia\n| Legal. Regulated by the Ministry of Education and the [[ICFES]] (Colombian Institute for the Promotion of Higher Education). The student would have to present a Public Validation Test and a State Test (Similar to SAT) if he/she wants to go to College.\n| N/A\n| <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www2.icfes.gov.co/|title=Novedades - Icfes Instituto Colombiano para la Evaluaci\u00f3n de la Educaci\u00f3n|author=|date=|website=www2.icfes.gov.co}}</ref>\n|-\n| Costa Rica\n| Illegal, public or private education is mandatory without known exceptions.\n| \n|<ref>{{cite web|url=https://homeschoolingcostarica.org|title=\u00bfEs legal el homeschooling en Costa Rica? No|author=|date=|website=homeschoolingcostarica.org}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://hslda.org/content/hs/international/CostaRica/default.asp|title=HSLDA - Home Schooling - Costa Rica|author=|date=|website=hslda.org}}</ref>\n|-\n| Cuba\n| Illegal, public education is mandatory without known exceptions.\n| Virtually no homeschooling*\n| [[Education in Cuba|WP]]{{Circular reference|date=February 2019}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.britannica.com/place/Cuba|title=Cuba - history - geography|author=|date=|website=Encyclopedia Britannica}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nationsencyclopedia.com/Americas/Cuba-EDUCATION.html|title=Education - Cuba|author=|date=|website=www.nationsencyclopedia.com}}</ref>\n|-\n| El Salvador\n| Illegal, public education is mandatory without known exceptions.\n| Virtually no homeschooling*\n|\n|-\n| Guatemala\n| Illegal, public education is mandatory without known exceptions.\n| Unknown\n| <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.britannica.com/place/Guatemala|title=Guatemala - History, Map, Flag, Population, & Facts|author=|date=|website=Encyclopedia Britannica}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nationsencyclopedia.com/Americas/Guatemala-EDUCATION.html|title=Educa